{"title_page": "Murray Sueter", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix = [[Rear-Admiral]]\n| name          =Murray Fraser Sueter\n| honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|size=100%|country=GBR|CB}}\n| image         =Captain Murray Sueter RN, 1915.jpg\n| caption       =Murray Sueter in 1915\n| birth_date          ={{Birth date|1872|09|06|df=yes}}\n| death_date          ={{Death date and age|1960|02|03|1872|09|06|df=yes}}\n| placeofburial_label = \n| placeofburial = \n| birth_place  =Alverstoke, Gosport\n| death_place  =Watlington, Oxfordshire\n| placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n| nickname      =\n| birth_name    =\n| allegiance    ={{flag|United Kingdom}}\n| branch        ={{navy|United Kingdom}}\n| serviceyears  =1886\u20131918 (officially retired 1920)\n| rank          =[[Rear-Admiral]]\n| servicenumber =\n| unit          =\n| commands      =\n| battles       =[[World War I]]\n| battles_label =\n| awards        =\n| relations     =[[Andrew Clarke (British Army officer, born 1824)|Sir Andrew Clarke]] (father-in-law)\n| laterwork     =Developed [[Empire Air Mail Scheme|Empire air mail postal services]]<br>[[Member of Parliament]]<br>Author\n}}\n\n[[Rear-Admiral]] '''Sir Murray Fraser Sueter''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CB}} (6 September 1872 \u2013 3 February 1960) was a [[Royal Navy|Royal Naval]] officer who was noted as a pioneer of [[naval aviation]] and later became a [[Member of Parliament]] (MP).\n\n==Naval career==\nSueter was born in [[Alverstoke]]. Coming from a naval background, he entered the [[Royal Navy]] as a cadet on [[HMS Prince of Wales (1860)|''Britannia'']] in 1886 before serving as a [[midshipman]] with [[HMS Swiftsure (1870)|HMS ''Swiftsure'']]. In 1894 he was promoted to  [[Lieutenant (navy)|lieutenant]] and in 1896 he was posted to [[HMS Vernon (shore establishment)|HMS ''Vernon'']] to become a specialist in [[torpedo]] warfare, afterwards serving on the staff. In 1899 he became Torpedo Officer on [[HMS Jupiter (1895)|HMS ''Jupiter'']].<ref name=\"oxforddnb.com\">[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/36368?_fromAuth=1 Oxford Dictionary of National Biography entry]</ref>  In May 1902 Sueter moved to [[Reginald Bacon]]'s [[submarine tender]] [[HMS Hazard (1894)|HMS ''Hazard'']],<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Naval & Military intelligence|day_of_week=Tuesday |date=22 April 1902 |page_number=12 |issue=36748| }}</ref> where he distinguished himself by aiding injured crew members of the [[A class submarine (1903)|submarine A.1]] after an explosion aboard. Sueter's book, ''The Evolution of the Submarine Boat, Mine and Torpedo'' (1907), was the result of his close work with [[submarines]] during this time.<ref name=\"oxforddnb.com\"/>\n\nHe married [[Andrew Clarke (administrator)|Andrew Clarke]]'s daughter, Elinor Mary \"Nell\" de Winton, in 1903, a year before his promotion to [[commander]] (he was made a [[Captain (Royal Navy)|captain]] in 1909). Elinor Sueter died on 15 December 1948.<ref>[http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/38503/pages/115 London Gazette Issue 38503] published on 4 January 1949</ref>\n\nMurray Sueter's technical skills saw him brought into the [[Naval Ordnance Department]] of the [[Admiralty]] and in 1909 he supervised the construction of [[airship]] [[HMA No. 1|''Mayfly'']], a new avenue of naval development.<ref name=\"oxforddnb.com\"/> As inspecting captain of airships he oversaw the failure of the experiment but was nonetheless given command of the Navy's [[Air Department]] in 1912. In this role he oversaw the creation of the [[Royal Naval Air Service]].<ref name=\"oxforddnb.com\"/>\n\nSueter continued his aerial innovations during the early stages of [[World War I]] including the [[Torpedo bomber|launching of torpedoes from aircraft]] and in 1915 he was promoted [[Commodore (Royal Navy)|commodore first class]] and appointed superintendent of aircraft construction. He sat on the government's \"[[Advisory Committee for Aeronautics]]\", located at the [[National Physical Laboratory (United Kingdom)|National Physical Laboratory]], under the chairmanship of [[Richard Glazebrook]] and presidency of [[John William Strutt, 3rd Baron Rayleigh|John Strutt, Lord Rayleigh]].<ref>{{Cite book| publisher=Constable and company Limited |last=Lanchester |first=Frederick William |authorlink= Frederick W. Lanchester |title=[[:s:Aircraft in Warfare (1916)|Aircraft in Warfare]] |location= London |year=1916 |page=163}}</ref>\n\nHe promoted the use of [[Armored car (military)|armoured car]]s for the defence of airfields in France. After the stalemate of the trenches developed the cars were sent to Russia and Egypt.<ref>under [[Oliver Locker-Lampson]] and the [[Duke of Westminster]] respectively</ref> His interest in the armoured car led to involvement in [[tank]] development.\n\nIn 1917, he clashed with the Admiralty and was posted to command the RNAS in Italy. While in Italy, Sueter sent a letter to [[George V|King George]] which incurred the displeasure of the [[Sea Lords]] and he was relieved of command. He was given no work from 1918 to 1920 when he was retired as a [[rear-admiral]].<ref name=\"oxforddnb.com\"/>\n\nAfter his naval service he worked with [[airmail]] provision and published a number of books, notably ''Airmen or Noahs'' (1928) an autobiography and critique of current naval practices and ''The Evolution of the Tank'' (1937). He was knighted in 1934.<ref name=\"oxforddnb.com\"/>\n\n==Politics==\nAfter his naval service Sueter entered politics as a member of the [[Anti-Waste League]] and was co-sponsored by them and the [[Independent Parliamentary Group]] for the [[1921 Hertford by-election]] which he won.<ref>see [[List of UK minor party and independent MPs elected]]</ref> He went on to join the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] and contested the [[1923 United Kingdom general election|1923 general election]] for them, winning election in [[Hertford (UK Parliament constituency)|Hertford]]. He went on to hold the seat until his retirement in 1945.<ref name=\"oxforddnb.com\"/> During the 1930s he was one of a number of Members of Parliament to become active in the [[Anglo-German Fellowship]].<ref>Martin Pugh, ''\"Hurrah For the Blackshirts!\" Fascists and Fascism in Britain Between the War'', Pimlico, 2006, p. 270</ref> Along with several other members of the group, including a number of parliamentarians, he accepted an invitation from [[Joachim von Ribbentrop]] to attend the 1936 [[Nuremberg Rally]].<ref>Richard Griffiths, ''Fellow Travellers on the Right'', Oxford University Press, 1983, p. 225</ref> He died in [[Watlington, Oxfordshire]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[John Cyril Porte]]\n*[[John Lankester Parker]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.gracesguide.co.uk/wiki/Murray_Sueter Murray Fraser Sueter biodata]\n*{{Rayment-hc|date=March 2012}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n|-\n{{s-new|reason=Department established from the<br>aviation responsibilities of [[Commander-in-Chief, The Nore|C-in-C the Nore]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Director of the [[Admiralty]] [[Air Department]]|years=1912 \u2013 1915}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Charles Vaughan-Lee|C L Vaughan-Lee]]<br><small>As Director of the Air Service</small>}}\n|-\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Noel Pemberton Billing]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[Hertford (UK Parliament constituency)|Hertford]]|years=[[1921 Hertford by-election|1921]]\u2013[[1945 United Kingdom general election|1945]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Derek Walker-Smith, Baron Broxbourne|Derek Walker-Smith]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sueter, Murray}}\n\n[[Category:1872 births]]\n[[Category:1960 deaths]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of the Bath]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Independent members of the House of Commons of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy admirals]]\n[[Category:Royal Naval Air Service aviators]]\n[[Category:Military aviation leaders of World War I]]\n[[Category:Submarine pioneers]]\n[[Category:People from Gosport]]\n[[Category:People from Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1918\u20131922]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1922\u20131923]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1923\u20131924]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1924\u20131929]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1929\u20131931]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1931\u20131935]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1935\u20131945]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix = [[Rear-Admiral]]\n| name          =Murray Fraser Sueter\n| honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|size=100%|country=GBR|CB}}\n| image         =Captain Murray Sueter RN, 1915.jpg\n| caption       =Murray Sueter in 1915\n| birth_date          ={{Birth date|1872|09|06|df=yes}}\n| death_date          ={{Death date and age|1960|02|03|1872|09|06|df=yes}}\n| placeofburial_label = \n| placeofburial = \n| birth_place  =Alverstoke, Gosport\n| death_place  =Watlington, Oxfordshire\n| placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n| nickname      =\n| birth_name    =\n| allegiance    ={{flag|United Kingdom}}\n| branch        ={{navy|United Kingdom}}\n| serviceyears  =1886\u20131918 (officially retired 1920)\n| rank          =[[Rear-Admiral]]\n| servicenumber =\n| unit          =\n| commands      =\n| battles       =[[World War I]]\n| battles_label =\n| awards        =\n| relations     =[[Andrew Clarke (administrator)|Sir Andrew Clarke]] (father-in-law)\n| laterwork     =Developed [[Empire Air Mail Scheme|Empire air mail postal services]]<br>[[Member of Parliament]]<br>Author\n}}\n\n[[Rear-Admiral]] '''Sir Murray Fraser Sueter''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CB}} (6 September 1872 \u2013 3 February 1960) was a [[Royal Navy|Royal Naval]] officer who was noted as a pioneer of [[naval aviation]] and later became a [[Member of Parliament]] (MP).\n\n==Naval career==\nSueter was born in [[Alverstoke]]. Coming from a naval background, he entered the [[Royal Navy]] as a cadet on [[HMS Prince of Wales (1860)|''Britannia'']] in 1886 before serving as a [[midshipman]] with [[HMS Swiftsure (1870)|HMS ''Swiftsure'']]. In 1894 he was promoted to  [[Lieutenant (navy)|lieutenant]] and in 1896 he was posted to [[HMS Vernon (shore establishment)|HMS ''Vernon'']] to become a specialist in [[torpedo]] warfare, afterwards serving on the staff. In 1899 he became Torpedo Officer on [[HMS Jupiter (1895)|HMS ''Jupiter'']].<ref name=\"oxforddnb.com\">[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/36368?_fromAuth=1 Oxford Dictionary of National Biography entry]</ref>  In May 1902 Sueter moved to [[Reginald Bacon]]'s [[submarine tender]] [[HMS Hazard (1894)|HMS ''Hazard'']],<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Naval & Military intelligence|day_of_week=Tuesday |date=22 April 1902 |page_number=12 |issue=36748| }}</ref> where he distinguished himself by aiding injured crew members of the [[A class submarine (1903)|submarine A.1]] after an explosion aboard. Sueter's book, ''The Evolution of the Submarine Boat, Mine and Torpedo'' (1907), was the result of his close work with [[submarines]] during this time.<ref name=\"oxforddnb.com\"/>\n\nHe married [[Andrew Clarke (administrator)|Andrew Clarke]]'s daughter, Elinor Mary \"Nell\" de Winton, in 1903, a year before his promotion to [[commander]] (he was made a [[Captain (Royal Navy)|captain]] in 1909). Elinor Sueter died on 15 December 1948.<ref>[http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/38503/pages/115 London Gazette Issue 38503] published on 4 January 1949</ref>\n\nMurray Sueter's technical skills saw him brought into the [[Naval Ordnance Department]] of the [[Admiralty]] and in 1909 he supervised the construction of [[airship]] [[HMA No. 1|''Mayfly'']], a new avenue of naval development.<ref name=\"oxforddnb.com\"/> As inspecting captain of airships he oversaw the failure of the experiment but was nonetheless given command of the Navy's [[Air Department]] in 1912. In this role he oversaw the creation of the [[Royal Naval Air Service]].<ref name=\"oxforddnb.com\"/>\n\nSueter continued his aerial innovations during the early stages of [[World War I]] including the [[Torpedo bomber|launching of torpedoes from aircraft]] and in 1915 he was promoted [[Commodore (Royal Navy)|commodore first class]] and appointed superintendent of aircraft construction. He sat on the government's \"[[Advisory Committee for Aeronautics]]\", located at the [[National Physical Laboratory (United Kingdom)|National Physical Laboratory]], under the chairmanship of [[Richard Glazebrook]] and presidency of [[John William Strutt, 3rd Baron Rayleigh|John Strutt, Lord Rayleigh]].<ref>{{Cite book| publisher=Constable and company Limited |last=Lanchester |first=Frederick William |authorlink= Frederick W. Lanchester |title=[[:s:Aircraft in Warfare (1916)|Aircraft in Warfare]] |location= London |year=1916 |page=163}}</ref>\n\nHe promoted the use of [[Armored car (military)|armoured car]]s for the defence of airfields in France. After the stalemate of the trenches developed the cars were sent to Russia and Egypt.<ref>under [[Oliver Locker-Lampson]] and the [[Duke of Westminster]] respectively</ref> His interest in the armoured car led to involvement in [[tank]] development.\n\nIn 1917, he clashed with the Admiralty and was posted to command the RNAS in Italy. While in Italy, Sueter sent a letter to [[George V|King George]] which incurred the displeasure of the [[Sea Lords]] and he was relieved of command. He was given no work from 1918 to 1920 when he was retired as a [[rear-admiral]].<ref name=\"oxforddnb.com\"/>\n\nAfter his naval service he worked with [[airmail]] provision and published a number of books, notably ''Airmen or Noahs'' (1928) an autobiography and critique of current naval practices and ''The Evolution of the Tank'' (1937). He was knighted in 1934.<ref name=\"oxforddnb.com\"/>\n\n==Politics==\nAfter his naval service Sueter entered politics as a member of the [[Anti-Waste League]] and was co-sponsored by them and the [[Independent Parliamentary Group]] for the [[1921 Hertford by-election]] which he won.<ref>see [[List of UK minor party and independent MPs elected]]</ref> He went on to join the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] and contested the [[1923 United Kingdom general election|1923 general election]] for them, winning election in [[Hertford (UK Parliament constituency)|Hertford]]. He went on to hold the seat until his retirement in 1945.<ref name=\"oxforddnb.com\"/> During the 1930s he was one of a number of Members of Parliament to become active in the [[Anglo-German Fellowship]].<ref>Martin Pugh, ''\"Hurrah For the Blackshirts!\" Fascists and Fascism in Britain Between the War'', Pimlico, 2006, p. 270</ref> Along with several other members of the group, including a number of parliamentarians, he accepted an invitation from [[Joachim von Ribbentrop]] to attend the 1936 [[Nuremberg Rally]].<ref>Richard Griffiths, ''Fellow Travellers on the Right'', Oxford University Press, 1983, p. 225</ref> He died in [[Watlington, Oxfordshire]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[John Cyril Porte]]\n*[[John Lankester Parker]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.gracesguide.co.uk/wiki/Murray_Sueter Murray Fraser Sueter biodata]\n*{{Rayment-hc|date=March 2012}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n|-\n{{s-new|reason=Department established from the<br>aviation responsibilities of [[Commander-in-Chief, The Nore|C-in-C the Nore]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Director of the [[Admiralty]] [[Air Department]]|years=1912 \u2013 1915}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Charles Vaughan-Lee|C L Vaughan-Lee]]<br><small>As Director of the Air Service</small>}}\n|-\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Noel Pemberton Billing]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[Hertford (UK Parliament constituency)|Hertford]]|years=[[1921 Hertford by-election|1921]]\u2013[[1945 United Kingdom general election|1945]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Derek Walker-Smith, Baron Broxbourne|Derek Walker-Smith]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sueter, Murray}}\n\n[[Category:1872 births]]\n[[Category:1960 deaths]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of the Bath]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Independent members of the House of Commons of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy admirals]]\n[[Category:Royal Naval Air Service aviators]]\n[[Category:Military aviation leaders of World War I]]\n[[Category:Submarine pioneers]]\n[[Category:People from Gosport]]\n[[Category:People from Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1918\u20131922]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1922\u20131923]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1923\u20131924]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1924\u20131929]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1929\u20131931]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1931\u20131935]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1935\u20131945]]\n", "name_user": "Tassedethe", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 - Repaired 1 link to disambiguation page -(You can help)-Andrew Clarke (administrator), 1 to be fixed -Andrew Clarke (administrator)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Murray_Sueter"}
